  footnotes: []
english:
  title: In Response to the Rhyme of the Yangzhou Official's Residence
  author: An Chuk
  language: eng
  text: |-
    On official paths I wander without haste,
    No rush to forge ahead through years ahead.
    Two years have come and gone within this tower—
    Bamboo fronds above the railing share their cool breath,
    While banyan trees that shade the gate
    Sway their ancient green through wisps of smoke.

    Traveling through, I see the people's toil,
    And grieve for what my country still requires.
    I've squandered the grace my lord has shown—
    Even heaven must turn away in shame.
    My talents are too meager for the task,
    Unable to open new paths of benefit and gain.
    How then could I make golden springs
    Bubble forth from hidden mountain streams?
  footnotes:
    - The 'Yangzhou Official's Residence' refers to the residence where the speaker serves as an official, likely in Yangzhou. The poem responds to another work written in the same rhyme scheme.
    - The imagery of banyan trees and bamboo evokes both the physical setting and the speaker's reflective mood—natural beauty shadowed by concern for duty.
    - The final image of 'golden springs from mountain streams' is a classical metaphor for creating prosperity and new opportunities through skillful governance.
